<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-04-26T23:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-04-26T23:00:00-05:00" n="633" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d633">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/4099</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_RPS1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Reinsch</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-04-27T12:00:00+08:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">April 27, 1917, 12 p.m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received April 27, 3
                                    p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>The military governors, now here in conference, are in favor of
                                declaring war, and the President and Parliament will most likely be
                                asked to make a decision next week. Premier stated to me that if
                                China entered the war the Chinese Government would be ready if need
                                be to furnish as many men as could be armed and equipped.</p>
                            <p>I beg to be informed whether under the law just passed it would be
                                possible to extend financial assistance to China in order to enable
                                the Chinese Government to prepare reserve forces for the war and
                                cooperate in other ways, particularly in the matter of food
                                supply.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="#p_RPS1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Reinsch</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>